VEver since I was a little girl
p4
aVseeing "Star Wars" for the first time,
p5
aVI've been fascinated by this idea
p6
aVof personal robots.
p7
aVAnd as a little girl,
p8
aVI loved the idea of a robot that interacted with us
p9
aVmuch more like a helpful, trusted sidekick \u2014
p10
aVsomething that would delight us, enrich our lives
p11
aVand help us save a galaxy or two.
p12
aVI knew robots like that didn't really exist,
p13
aVbut I knew I wanted to build them.
p14
aa(lp15
VSo 20 years pass \u2014
p16
aVI am now a graduate student at MIT
p17
aVstudying artificial intelligence,
p18
aVthe year is 1997,
p19
aVand NASA has just landed the first robot on Mars.
p20
aVBut robots are still not in our home, ironically.
p21
aVAnd I remember thinking about
p22
aVall the reasons why that was the case.
p23
aVBut one really struck me.
p24
aVRobotics had really been about interacting with things,
p25
aVnot with people \u2014
p26
aVcertainly not in a social way that would be natural for us
p27
aVand would really help people accept robots
p28
aVinto our daily lives.
p29
aVFor me, that was the white space; that's what robots could not do yet.
p30
aVAnd so that year, I started to build this robot, Kismet,
p31
aVthe world's first social robot.
p32
aVThree years later \u2014
p33
aVa lot of programming,
p34
aVworking with other graduate students in the lab \u2014
p35
aVKismet was ready to start interacting with people.
p36
